The political life of Aristotle looked more and more
like a
masquerade of business interests in dis-
quise which, far from attracting the allegiance
of free men everywhere, could only repel them.
Then what of the cultural life? Did this
haps nurtuve a genuinely civilizing impule
which might in time become social fact
per-
and counteract the obsession with economics
which had grown up during the Monn's
first two centuries 2
